column26: MSS 571 titled âDevelopment status of the SiPM coupled scintillation detector for the DEGAS array in FAIRâ is in fact the second abstract paper (other one ID no. 569) submitted by the same authors on similar work related to SiPM read-out, except for the targeted experiments are different. Nothing is mentioned in the text about the DEGAS array, while a lot have been talked about Compton suppressor and its function which is available in standard textbook. The SiPM used in this paper is from a different manufacturer (SensL Ltd), while that used in the other paper (Ref ID no. 569) by the same authors is from Hamamatsu. Since SiPM / MPPC are the same device with variation in some of the characteristics (eg. pixel density, bias voltage, cross talk, dark noise, etc.), it is my suggestion to combine the two papers into one, with reduction in the introduction section by cutting down on descriptions of Compton shield, principle of operation of silicon photomultipliers, etc. A few words and comparison table of SiPM and MPPC will also add values to the abstract rather than inclusion of storage scope traces capture images. Some of the trace images are distorted as well (se Fig 2 of Ref ID 569). I strongly encourage the authors to combine the two manuscripts into one and re-submit which may be accepted, if found suitable.

column5: Efficiency of CeBr3 detector: Simulations and.. measurements using a positron emitter
column7: S Panwar;V Ranga;G Anil Kumar
column26: â¢	MSS 572 titled âEfficiency of CeBr3 detector: Simulations and measurements using a positron emitterâ exploits the usage of coincidence summing technique for obtaining correctly the absolute efficiency. The work is in line with that presented in a published paper (Ref 4) and in that sense, these are not new results. However, given the fact that the measurements were done with a CeBr3 detector of perhaps different origin and geometry, I recommend acceptance of the abstract for symposium presentation. However, a few suggestions for improvement and a few corrections due to oversight by the authors are given below. These should be corrected in a revised manuscript for the book of abstract. A) first page, 2nd para: deamination --> determination; B) same para, 2nd line from bottom: resolving --> resolving time of. As such, the results section has very limited / incomplete results to display or present. I understand that the detailed work will be presented during the symposium. One plot of absolute corrected efficiency obtained from simulation should have added value to the abstract. The authors may consider revising the abstract by taking care of the above observations.

column26: â¢	MSS 584 titled "Development of bakelite resistive plate chamber based muon tomography system" contains presentation of a few very important information on single gap RPC characterization including efficiency and I-V characteristics to prove that the 6 RPCs are individually working as expected. These results are not new. A few simulation results or algorithm development for muon tomography would have added value to the abstract, but I suppose the group will work on it and present their results at the symposium. Noticed a few typos or statements that can create confusion. The authors may correct them in a revised abstract. A) Sec 3 A: What is meant by the breakdown voltage? Mentioned as 5200 â 5600 V. On the other hand, this is around 11000 V in the plots of Figs 2, 3 & 4 where the leakage current tend to increase asymptotically. If otherwise, please check and correct. B) In sec 3B, the context of master trigger is not clear. Apparently, the five out of six RPCs stack coincidence by cosmic muon may generate master trigger, but in this case it appears to be generated by scintillators in a cosmic muon test bench. A mention of the usage of a scintillator based cosmic muon test bench as the first line of the para will clarify the confusion.

column5: The Measurement of Efficiency and.. Resolution for CdZnTe and.. NaI(Tl) detectors
column7: Dalpat Meena;S.K. Gupta
column26: MSS 621 titled "The Measurement of Efficiency and Resolution for CdZnTe and NaI(Tl) detectors" by Dalpat Meena* and S.K.Gupta: The paper contains some details of efficiency and resolution comparion of CZT detector with large area NaI(Tl) detector, but the basic difference between the two generic classes (semiconductor and scintillator) are not indicated. The authors used standard gamma ray sources for gamma rays of different energies in the range of ~350 keV to 1332 keV. It is not clear why they avoided lower energies, where it is important to know the efficiency, and a deviation from the exponential curve is expected due to the role of the front absorber. In fact, one of the reference sources used in the measurement has a gamma ray line at 81 keV which could have been used for the measurements. Furthermore, the results that have been presented are well known and as such, no new or interesting result is brought out. Because of limited value addition, the paper is not considered suitable for presentation in the international symposium.
